To prove that the probability of the product of $n$ digits (each from $\{1, \dots, 9\}$) being divisible by 10 is $1 - (8/9)^n - (5/9)^n + (4/9)^n$, we use the principle of inclusion-exclusion. The product is divisible by 10 if and only if it is divisible by both 2 and 5.

Let $E_2$ be the event that the product is divisible by 2 (at least one digit is even: $\{2, 4, 6, 8\}$).
Let $E_5$ be the event that the product is divisible by 5 (at least one digit is 5: $\{5\}$).
We want to find $P(E_2 \cap E_5) = 1 - P(E_2^c \cup E_5^c) = 1 - (P(E_2^c) + P(E_5^c) - P(E_2^c \cap E_5^c))$.
$E_2^c$ is the event that all digits are odd: $\{1, 3, 5, 7, 9\}$, so $P(E_2^c) = (5/9)^n$.
$E_5^c$ is the event that no digit is 5: $\{1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7, 8, 9\}$, so $P(E_5^c) = (8/9)^n$.
$E_2^c \cap E_5^c$ is the event that all digits are odd and not 5: $\{1, 3, 7, 9\}$, so $P(E_2^c \cap E_5^c) = (4/9)^n$.
Substituting these, we get $P = 1 - ((5/9)^n + (8/9)^n - (4/9)^n) = 1 - (8/9)^n - (5/9)^n + (4/9)^n$.

